<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n15029c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n15" href="#n15029c">N15 (VI.D.2)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n15all.htm#n15029c"> 29(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> gravemound / &mdash; breaker</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The use of saga-telling to enliven festive gatherings is farther illustrated in the account of a wedding, which took place at Reykh&oacute;lar (in the north-west of Iceland) in the year 1119. &ldquo;Hr&oacute;lf of Sk&oacute;lmarness,&rdquo; it says, &ldquo;told the saga about Hr&ouml;ngrvi&eth; the viking, and &Oacute;laf, king of the Lithsmen, and the <mark>breaking into the grave-mound</mark> of Thr&aacute;in the berserk, and Hr&oacute;mund Gripsson, and many verses along with it. <small> W. A. Craige, <a name="ICEL" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ICEL"><cite title="source">The Icelandic Sagas</cite></a>, (1913) 17</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c15205c" href="c15all.htm#c15205c">VI.C.15:205(c)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
